  "market_context": "NQ on the hourly is in a consolidation range; price swept the high side of the range, made an aggressive move lower, and closed back inside the range, signalling a bearish continuation bias for the day with downside objectives.",
  "key_observation": "After the hourly reversal, the 5-minute chart provides multiple mechanical continuation short entries — each one requires price to first retrace into a fair value gap or sweep a short-term high, then close through the up-close candles to form a valid bearish order block.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the 1H, identify a consolidation range where price swept the high and closed back inside, establishing a bearish bias targeting the lower side of the range.",
    "Step 2: Drop to the 5-minute chart via time frame alignment to seek either the reversal candle or, preferably, a continuation entry.",
    "Step 3: Note that no valid order block can form until price retraces into a fair value gap or sweeps a short-term high — the initial expansion off the low offers no mechanical setup.",
    "Step 4: Wait for the first qualifying continuation: price retraces up into a FVG / sweeps a short-term high, then closes below the up-close candle, forming a bearish order block — take the short targeting the range low.",
    "Step 5: Disqualify a candidate continuation where price closes lower but did not first reach into a FVG or sweep a high (mechanically invalid).",
    "Step 6: Identify a second valid continuation when price again rallies into a fair value gap and closes through the up-close candles, providing a later entry toward the same downside target.",
    "Step 7: Manage trades to at least 2R as price delivers lower toward the targeted liquidity."
  ],
  "outcome": "Multiple valid continuation short entries delivered, with the trade reaching 2R to the downside.",
  "lessons": "Continuation entries must be mechanically defined: price must retrace into a fair value gap or sweep a short-term high before closing through the opposing candle series. Moves that simply grind without those triggers are missed trades — not setups to chase.",
